{
  "The Himalayas were formed by:": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions, particularly regarding since as": "",
  "Normal faulting, particularly regarding fold as": "",
  "Compression from the collision of the Indian and Eurasian plates": "",
  "Erosion, particularly regarding neither under the": "",
  "The Himalayas are fold mountains formed by the ongoing collision between the Indian and Eurasian continental plates. Since neither plate can easily subduct, the crust crumples and is thrust upward, creating the world's tallest mountain range.": "",
  "Fault-block mountains form under _____ stress.": "",
  "Shear": "",
  "No stress at all": "",
  "Tensional (extensional)": "",
  "Compressional": "",
  "Fault-block mountains form when tensional (extensional) forces pull the crust apart, causing blocks of rock to drop down or be pushed up along normal faults. The Sierra Nevada and the Grand Tetons are classic examples.": "",
  "In a normal fault, the hanging wall moves:": "",
  "Not at all": "",
  "Sideways": "",
  "Up relative to the footwall": "",
  "Down relative to the footwall": "",
  "In a normal fault, tensional forces cause the hanging wall (the block above the fault plane) to move downward relative to the footwall. Normal faults are associated with extensional tectonic settings like rift zones.": "",
  "An anticline is:": "",
  "A volcanic feature": "",
  "A downward fold in rock layers": "",
  "An upward arch-shaped fold in rock layers": "",
  "A type of fault": "",
  "An anticline is a fold in rock layers that arches upward like an inverted U. The oldest rocks are found in the center (core) of the fold. Anticlines are commonly formed by compressional forces at convergent plate boundaries.": "",
  "A strike-slip fault produces _____ motion.": "",
  "Horizontal (lateral)": "",
  "Diagonal": "",
  "Up-and-down vertical": "",
  "Circular": "",
  "A strike-slip fault involves horizontal (lateral) movement where blocks of rock slide past each other. The San Andreas Fault is a famous right-lateral strike-slip fault where the Pacific Plate moves northwest relative to the North American Plate.": "",
  "Mt. Rainier is an example of a _____ mountain.": "",
  "Dome": "",
  "Fold": "",
  "Volcanic": "",
  "Fault-block": "",
  "Mt. Rainier is a volcanic mountain (stratovolcano) in the Cascade Range, built by successive eruptions that deposited layers of lava and pyroclastic material. Volcanic mountains are constructed by the accumulation of erupted material rather than by folding or faulting.": "",
  "The Appalachian Mountains are much shorter than the Himalayas because they:": "",
  "Were formed by a different process than the Himalayas": "",
  "Are still being compressed upward": "",
  "Were never tall": "",
  "Are much older and have been heavily eroded over hundreds of millions of years": "",
  "The Appalachians formed 480-300 million years ago and were once as tall as the Himalayas. Hundreds of millions of years of erosion have worn them down to their current relatively modest elevations, demonstrating how erosion counteracts mountain building over geological time.": "",
  "The Black Hills of South Dakota are _____ mountains.": "",
  "The Black Hills are dome mountains formed when magma pushed up overlying rock without erupting. Subsequent erosion exposed the uplifted rocks, creating a dome-shaped feature with the oldest rocks exposed at the center.": "",
  "A graben is a:": "",
  "Volcanic crater": "",
  "Downdropped block between two normal faults that forms a valley": "",
  "Mountain peak formed by compression": "",
  "Uplifted block between faults": "",
  "A graben is a block of rock that has dropped down between two parallel normal faults due to extensional forces. Grabens form rift valleys, such as the East African Rift Valley, which is a classic example of this tectonic structure.": "",
  "In a reverse fault, the hanging wall moves:": "",
  "In a reverse fault, compressional forces push the hanging wall upward relative to the footwall. Reverse faults are associated with convergent plate boundaries and mountain building. A thrust fault is a reverse fault with a low angle of dip (less than 45 degrees).": "",
  "What is orogeny?": "",
  "The process of volcanic eruptions creating new islands": "",
  "The erosion of mountains by glaciers and rivers": "",
  "The study of ancient organisms preserved in rock": "",
  "The process of mountain building, typically through folding, faulting, and uplift caused by tectonic forces": "",
  "Orogeny refers to the processes of mountain formation, including folding, faulting, volcanic activity, and uplift driven by tectonic plate interactions. Major orogenies are typically associated with convergent plate boundaries.": "",
  "What is a syncline?": "",
  "A volcanic vent that produces only gas": "",
  "A type of fault with horizontal motion": "",
  "A downward trough-shaped fold in rock layers where the youngest rocks are found at the center": "",
  "An upward arch in folded rock layers": "",
  "A syncline is a fold in rock layers that forms a trough or U-shape. Unlike an anticline (where the oldest rocks are in the center), a syncline has the youngest rocks at its center and older rocks on the limbs.": "",
  "What is a fold mountain?": "",
  "A mountain built by successive volcanic eruptions": "",
  "A mountain formed when rock layers are compressed and buckled into folds by convergent plate forces": "",
  "A mountain formed by blocks of rock being lifted along faults": "",
  "A mountain created when magma pushes rock upward without erupting": "",
  "Fold mountains form when tectonic compression forces rock layers to buckle and fold. They are typically formed at convergent boundaries where plates collide. The Himalayas, Alps, and Appalachians are all fold mountains.": "",
  "What is a horst?": "",
  "An uplifted block of rock between normal faults, forming elevated terrain": "",
  "A fold in rock layers caused by compression": "",
  "A volcanic cone built from erupted material": "",
  "A downdropped block of rock forming a valley": "",
  "A horst is a raised block of rock between two parallel normal faults. Horsts and grabens together create the characteristic alternating ridges and valleys seen in regions of crustal extension, like the Basin and Range Province of the western United States.": "",
  "What is isostatic rebound?": "",
  "The gradual uplift of crust after a heavy load like glacial ice or eroded mountain rock is removed": "",
  "The bouncing of seismic waves off Earth's core": "",
  "The sinking of crust under heavy ice sheets": "",
  "The movement of tectonic plates away from mid-ocean ridges": "",
  "Isostatic rebound is the rise of the Earth's crust after a heavy load has been removed. Scandinavia is still rising by about 1 cm per year as the crust rebounds from the weight of ice sheets that melted over 10,000 years ago.": "",
  "What is a thrust fault?": "",
  "A fault that only occurs at transform boundaries": "",
  "A fracture with no displacement of rock on either side": "",
  "A low-angle reverse fault (less than 45 degrees) where the hanging wall is pushed over the footwall, allowing large horizontal displacement": "",
  "A fault with horizontal, side-to-side motion": "",
  "A thrust fault is a reverse fault with a dip angle less than 45 degrees. The low angle allows large sheets of rock to be pushed horizontally over great distances. Thrust faults are common in mountain belts and can stack older rocks on top of younger ones.": "",
  "What does 'strike and dip' describe in geology?": "",
  "The height and width of a mountain peak": "",
  "The orientation (compass direction) and angle of tilt of rock layers or fault planes in the field": "",
  "The temperature and pressure conditions underground": "",
  "The speed and direction of lava flow": "",
  "Strike is the compass direction of the line formed by the intersection of a tilted rock layer with a horizontal surface, while dip is the angle of tilt measured from horizontal. Together they describe the three-dimensional orientation of geological features.": "",
  "What is a joint in geology?": "",
  "A fracture or crack in rock along which there has been no relative displacement of the sides": "",
  "The point where two tectonic plates meet": "",
  "A fracture in rock along which there has been significant displacement": "",
  "A connection between two types of sedimentary rock": "",
  "A joint is a fracture in rock where the two sides have not moved relative to each other (unlike a fault, which has displacement). Joints form from stress, cooling, or unloading and are important in controlling erosion patterns and groundwater flow.": "",
  "What is a normal fault?": "",
  "A fault that has not moved in recorded history": "",
  "A fault with only horizontal movement": "",
  "A fault caused by tensional forces where the hanging wall moves down relative to the footwall": "",
  "A fault caused by compressional forces where the hanging wall moves up": "",
  "A normal fault forms under tensional (extensional) stress where the crust is being pulled apart. The hanging wall block drops down relative to the footwall. Normal faults are characteristic of rift zones and divergent boundaries.": "",
  "What is a dome mountain?": "",
  "A volcano with a rounded summit": "",
  "A mountain formed when magma pushes overlying rock upward without erupting, creating a broad, dome-shaped uplift": "",
  "A mountain formed by folding of rock layers at a convergent boundary": "",
  "A mountain formed by glacial deposition": "",
  "Dome mountains form when magma pushes upward from below, uplifting the overlying rock layers into a dome shape without breaking through to the surface. Erosion then removes the softer overlying layers, exposing the harder rocks beneath. The Black Hills are a classic example.": "",
  "A petroleum geologist is searching for oil deposits in a sedimentary basin. She focuses her exploration on anticline structures. Why are anticlines favorable locations for oil accumulation?": "",
  "Oil is heavier than rock and sinks into anticlines": "",
  "Anticlines are always located near the ocean where oil forms": "",
  "Anticlines contain volcanic rock that generates oil": "",
  "Oil migrates upward through porous rock and becomes trapped at the crest of anticlines beneath an impermeable cap rock layer": "",
  "Oil and gas are less dense than water and migrate upward through porous reservoir rock. In an anticline, the arch shape and overlying impermeable cap rock create a trap that prevents further upward migration, concentrating hydrocarbons at the crest of the fold.": "",
  "The Basin and Range Province in the western United States features parallel mountain ranges separated by flat valleys. A geology student asks how this distinctive landscape formed. What is the correct tectonic explanation?": "",
  "Ancient rivers carved parallel valleys between pre-existing mountains": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions built the mountain ranges in parallel lines": "",
  "Compression from plate collision folded the crust into parallel ridges": "",
  "Extensional forces are pulling the crust apart, creating alternating horsts (mountain ranges) and grabens (valleys) along normal faults": "",
  "The Basin and Range Province formed from crustal extension where the lithosphere is being pulled apart. This creates a series of normal faults, producing alternating uplifted blocks (horsts forming mountain ranges) and downdropped blocks (grabens forming valleys).": "",
  "Scandinavia is currently rising at about 1 cm per year, even though no tectonic compression is occurring there. Ports that were at sea level centuries ago are now several meters above the waterline. What process explains this ongoing uplift?": "",
  "Sea levels are dropping globally, exposing formerly submerged coastline": "",
  "Isostatic rebound: the crust is slowly rising after the removal of heavy ice sheets that depressed it during the last ice age": "",
  "Volcanic magma is pushing the crust upward from below": "",
  "Tectonic plates are lifting Scandinavia at a convergent boundary": "",
  "During the last ice age, ice sheets several kilometers thick depressed the Scandinavian crust. Since the ice melted about 10,000 years ago, the crust has been slowly rebounding upward toward gravitational equilibrium (isostasy). This process is still ongoing and measurable by GPS.": "",
  "A civil engineer is planning a road cut through a hillside and discovers that the rock layers dip steeply toward the road. The geologist warns that this orientation creates a significant landslide hazard. Why is the dip direction important for construction safety?": "",
  "Steeply dipping layers always contain groundwater that floods roads": "",
  "Dipping rock layers look unattractive along a road": "",
  "Dipping layers indicate the road is too close to a volcano": "",
  "Rock layers that dip toward a road cut can slide along bedding planes when support is removed, creating dangerous rockslides": "",
  "When a road cut removes material that was supporting steeply dipping rock layers, the layers can slide along their bedding planes toward the road under gravity. Understanding strike and dip is essential for safe construction in areas with tilted rock.": "",
  "The Alps, Himalayas, and Andes are all actively growing mountain ranges, while the Appalachians are slowly getting shorter. What fundamental difference explains why some mountain ranges grow while others shrink?": "",
  "Active mountain ranges are at convergent boundaries where tectonic uplift exceeds erosion, while the Appalachians are no longer at an active boundary and erosion dominates": "",
  "Climate differences alone determine whether mountains grow or shrink": "",
  "Growing mountains have better soil that prevents erosion": "",
  "Only volcanic mountains can grow; all fold mountains shrink": "",
  "Mountain height is a balance between tectonic uplift and erosion. The Alps, Himalayas, and Andes are at active convergent boundaries where uplift exceeds erosion. The Appalachians are no longer at an active boundary, so erosion has been wearing them down for hundreds of millions of years.": "",
  "Geologists mapping a remote region discover that older rock layers are sitting on top of younger ones over a wide area. Under normal conditions, older rocks should be below younger ones. What geological structure best explains this observation?": "",
  "A normal fault that dropped the younger rocks below the older ones": "",
  "Erosion that removed the middle rock layers": "",
  "Volcanic activity that deposited old lava on top of young sediments": "",
  "A large thrust fault that pushed a sheet of older rock over the top of younger rock during mountain building": "",
  "Large thrust faults can push sheets of older rock over younger rock for many kilometers during mountain-building events. This reversal of the normal superposition sequence is a diagnostic feature of thrust faults and is common in fold-and-thrust belts.": "",
  "A dam is being constructed across a valley. During site investigation, geologists find that the valley sits on a graben (downdropped block between normal faults). Why should this finding concern the engineers?": "",
  "Rock in grabens is always too soft to support a dam": "",
  "Grabens are always too wide for dam construction": "",
  "The normal faults defining the graben may still be active, posing earthquake risk, and the fractured rock may allow water to leak around or under the dam": "",
  "Grabens always contain toxic minerals that contaminate water": "",
  "Building a dam on a graben presents multiple concerns: the bounding normal faults may still be seismically active, and the extensively fractured rock along fault zones can create pathways for water to leak around or under the dam, potentially compromising its integrity.": "",
  "Marine fossils have been found near the summit of Mount Everest (8,849 m elevation). How did ocean organisms end up at the top of the world's tallest mountain?": "",
  "The fossils formed in place from minerals in the mountain rock": "",
  "A massive tsunami deposited marine organisms at high elevation": "",
  "Ancient birds carried the fossils to the mountain summit": "",
  "The limestone at Everest's summit was originally marine sediment on an ancient seafloor that was uplifted to extreme heights by the collision of the Indian and Eurasian plates": "",
  "The limestone near Everest's summit contains fossils of marine organisms like crinoids and trilobites that lived on the floor of the ancient Tethys Sea. The collision of India with Eurasia uplifted these seafloor sediments to nearly 9,000 m elevation over tens of millions of years.": "",
  "The East African Rift Valley is widening at about 6-7 mm per year. Scientists predict it will eventually split Africa into two separate landmasses. What type of geological structure is the rift valley, and what forces are creating it?": "",
  "It is an anticline formed by compression from a nearby convergent boundary": "",
  "It is a volcanic caldera formed by a massive eruption": "",
  "It is a strike-slip fault system formed by shear forces": "",
  "It is a graben system formed by extensional (tensional) forces that are pulling the African plate apart along normal faults": "",
  "The East African Rift is a continental rift zone consisting of a series of grabens (downdropped blocks between normal faults) formed by extensional forces pulling Africa apart. The rift features active volcanism, earthquakes, and progressive widening that will eventually form a new ocean basin.": "",
  "A homeowner in a mountainous area notices that the rock layers visible in a cliff behind their house are folded into an arch shape. Water appears to be seeping from the sides of the fold but not from the top. Based on your knowledge of geological structures, what is the most likely explanation?": "",
  "The fold is an anticline, and water flows downward along the tilted permeable rock layers on the limbs of the fold, while the crest may have fractured impermeable rock that redirects water to the sides": "",
  "The water table is always flat regardless of rock structure, particularly regarding springs under normal circumstances": "",
  "The rock is too hot at the top of the fold for water to exist based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "Underground rivers only flow in straight lines, not over folds when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "In an anticline, the rock layers tilt downward on both limbs away from the crest. Groundwater tends to flow along permeable layers following the dip, emerging as springs on the sides of the fold. The crest of an anticline often has tension fractures that can alter flow patterns.": ""
}